Like [[Transportation in the United States|transportation in the rest of the United States]], the primary mode of local '''transportation in Portland, Oregon''' is the [[automobile]]. The [[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] has a regional master plan in which [[transit-oriented development]] plays a major role.<ref>http://library.oregonmetro.gov/files//tod_final_report.pdf</ref>  This approach, part of the [[new urbanism]], promotes mixed-use and high-density development around [[light rail]] stops and [[List of TriMet transit centers|transit centers]], and the investment of the metropolitan area's share of federal tax dollars into multiple modes of [[transport]]ation.  In the United States, this focus is atypical in an era when [[automobile]] use led many areas to neglect their core cities in favor of development along [[interstate highway]]s, in [[suburb]]s, and [[satellite city|satellite cities]].<ref>{{cite news |title= Focus: Portland; So Long Cars, Hello People |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/05/31/realestate/focus-portland-so-long-cars-hello-people.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |author=Timothy Egan |date=May 31, 1987 |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>
