==Mass transit==
Portland has a comprehensive [[public transportation]] system. The bus and rail system is operated by [[TriMet]], its name reflecting the three [[Portland metropolitan area|metropolitan area]] counties it serves ([[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah]], [[Clackamas County, Oregon|Clackamas]], and [[Washington County, Oregon|Washington]]).  Portland's rate of public transit use (12.6% of commutes in 2008) is comparable to much larger cities like [[Los Angeles]], and higher than in most similarly sized U.S. cities, but is lower than in some others, such as [[Baltimore]] and [[Seattle]].<ref name="ACS2008">{{cite web
|title=American Community Survey 2006, Table S0802
|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]]
|url=http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/STGeoSearchByListServlet?ds_name=ACS_2008_1YR_G00_
}}</ref> Transit service between Portland and [[Vancouver, Washington]], the second-largest city in the metropolitan area, is provided by [[C-Tran (Washington)|C-Tran]], with a small number of express routes.

[[File:Portland Transit Mall with cyclists crossing.jpg|thumb|left|Buses and bikes in downtown Portland.]]
Within the [[Downtown Portland|downtown area]] (the city center) is the [[Portland Transit Mall]], a transit-priority corridor on which buses and light rail trains from many different parts of the region converge.  First opened in 1977, and for three decades served only by buses, the transit mall underwent major changes in 2009.  Tracks for light rail ([[MAX Light Rail|MAX]]) were added, bus stops spaced farther apart, and the left lane opened to general traffic (but with right turns prohibited).<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Rose | first = Joseph | authorlink = Joseph Rose
  | title = Weave through TriMet's work in downtown Portland
  | newspaper = [[The Oregonian]]
  | date = January 22, 2009
  | url = http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/01/bus_mall.html
  | accessdate = April 15, 2013
}}</ref>  To facilitate this major renovation and rebuilding, lasting more than two years, all bus routes using the mall were diverted to other streets (mainly 3rd and 4th avenues) starting in January 2007.<ref>{{cite news | last = Redden| first = Jim| title = Bye-bye, bus mall as we know it| newspaper = [[Portland Tribune]]| date = January 12, 2007| url = http://thetribonline.net/news/story.php?story_id=116855917359029300 | accessdate = December 19, 2012 }}</ref>  The transit mall reopened to buses on May 24, 2009,<ref>{{cite news
  | last = Rivera  | first = Dylan
  | title = Buses return to Portland's revamped transit mall
  | newspaper = [[The Oregonian]]
  | date = May 26, 2009
  | url = http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2009/05/buses_return_to_portlands_reva.html
  | accessdate = October 1, 2009
}}</ref> and operator training runs on the new light-rail tracks took place during the late spring and summer.<ref>{{cite news
  | title = Light-rail operator training begins on Portland Mall
  | newspaper = [[Portland Business Journal]]
  | date = May 1, 2009
  | url = http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily66.html?surround=lfn
  | accessdate = October 1, 2009
}}</ref> Light rail service on the transit mall was introduced on August 30, 2009, when the [[MAX Yellow Line]] moved to the mall from its previous routing.<ref>{{cite news| title = New MAX line opens downtown| newspaper = [[Portland Tribune]]| date = August 28, 2009| url = http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=125148305025064100| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608052546/http://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=125148305025064100 |archivedate= June 8, 2011|accessdate = February 24, 2016}}</ref>  The new [[MAX Green Line]] opened 13 days later, on September 12, and it also serves the downtown transit mall.<ref name="riderspack">{{cite news
  | last = Rivera | first = Dylan
  | title = Riders pack MAX Green Line on first day of service
  | newspaper = [[The Oregonian]]
  | date = September 13, 2009
