The [[Portland Streetcar]] is a two-line [[streetcar]] system serving the central part of Portland—[[Downtown Portland|downtown]] and the areas immediately surrounding downtown. The system's first line opened in 2001 and, with later extensions, now follows a {{convert|3.9|mi|km|adj=on}} route<ref name="ptj2010-1">Morgan, Steve. "Expansion for Portland's MAX: New routes and equipment", pp. 38-40. ''[[Passenger Train Journal]]'', "2010:1" issue (1st quarter, 2010).  White River Productions.</ref> from [[Legacy Good Samaritan Medical Center]] at NW 23rd Avenue through inner-Northwest and Southwest, including the [[Pearl District]] and [[Portland State University]], to the new [[South Waterfront]] neighborhood, where it connects to the [[Portland Aerial Tram]].<ref>[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/history.php Portland Streetcar: Streetcar History] from portlandstreetcar.org</ref>  In 2012, this route was given the designation [[NS Line (Portland Streetcar)|North-South Line]], or NS Line.

The system's second line opened in 2012 and extended service across the [[Willamette River]] to the [[Lloyd District]] and the [[Central Eastside Industrial District|Central Eastside]].<ref name=trib-2012sep22>{{cite news|last=Redden|first=Jim|title=East side streetcar service begins|newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]]|date=September 22, 2012|url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/115602-east-side-streetcar-service-begins|accessdate=December 27, 2012}}</ref>  The [[Federal Transit Administration|federal]] share of funding for this $148-million project, a {{convert|3.3|mi|km|adj=on}} extension and fleet expansion,<ref name=trib-2012sep22/> was approved in April 2009,<ref name="Fedsgive">{{cite news
  | title = Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar
  | newspaper = [[Portland Business Journal]]
  | date = April 30, 2009
  | url = http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn
  | accessdate = December 27, 2012
}}</ref> and construction began in August 2009.  Originally named the [[Central Loop (Portland Streetcar)|Central Loop]] Line, or CL Line, it was renamed the A Loop (clockwise) and B Loop (counterclockwise) in 2015, when it was extended from the eastside across the Tilikum Crossing bridge and also along the NS Line from South Waterfront to Portland State University.  See [[Portland Streetcar#Eastside line|Portland Streetcar (Eastside line)]] and [[Loop Service (Portland Streetcar)]] for more detail.

The [[Willamette Shore Trolley]] is a seasonal, volunteer-operated [[heritage streetcar]] service established in 1990 – after a 1987 trial run – for the purpose of preserving an approximately {{convert|6|mi|km|sigfig=1|adj=on}} former [[Southern Pacific Transportation Company|Southern Pacific]] railroad right-of-way running south from Portland to [[Lake Oswego, Oregon|Lake Oswego]] for possible future transit use.  Plans to extend the Portland Streetcar along the right-of-way were mothballed in early 2012, but remain under consideration for the long term.<ref name="LO suspends">{{cite news|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/lake-oswego/index.ssf/2012/01/lake_oswego_officially_suspend.html|title=Lake Oswego officially suspends streetcar plans with goal of retaining Willamette Shore right-of-way for future transit use|last=Bailey Jr.|first=Everton|newspaper=The Oregonian|date=January 25, 2012|accessdate=February 28, 2014}}</ref> The right-of-way was acquired by a consortium of local governmental entities in 1988 for this purpose.<ref name="willamette-shore-metro">{{cite web| title = Lake Oswego to Portland transit project: Willamette Shore line right-of-way| publisher = [[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] | url = http://www.oregonmetro.gov/index.cfm/go/by.web/id=25070| accessdate = February 28, 2014}}</ref>

===Commuter rail===
TriMet's [[WES Commuter Rail]] connects the cities of [[Wilsonville, Oregon|Wilsonville]], [[Tualatin, Oregon|Tualatin]], [[Tigard, Oregon|Tigard]] and [[Beaverton, Oregon|Beaverton]].  It is one of only three suburb-to-suburb [[commuter rail]] lines in the country,{{citation needed|date=January 2011}} along with [[Tri-Rail]] in [[Miami]] and the [[Inland Empire-Orange County Line]] operated by [[Metrolink (Southern California)|Metrolink]] between San Bernardino and Oceanside, Calif.  Rather than electric railcars like those of MAX, the line uses [[Federal Railroad Administration|FRA]]-compliant [[diesel multiple unit]]s running on existing [[Portland and Western Railroad]] freight tracks.  The first rides open to the general public took place on Friday, January 30, 2009, and regular service began on Monday, February 2, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=44156 |title=WES' first day&nbsp;— 'I plan on using it every day' |author=Leah Weissman |newspaper=[[Beaverton Valley Times]]|date=February 5, 2009 <!--(later redated Feb. 4 by the publisher)-->| accessdate=November 19, 2015}}</ref>

[[Amtrak]] also exists as a rail commuting option in the Portland area with the [[Amtrak Cascades]] providing daily service between Portland and neighboring Oregon City.<ref>http://amtrakcascades.com/Schedules.htm</ref> While the frequency is less than that of [[TriMet]], the 20-minute ride from Oregon City is faster, has cheaper tickets, and is arguably a more comfortable service.<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/pacific-northwest-news/index.ssf/2012/03/amtrak_gaining_popularity_amon.html</ref>

See the [[Transportation in Portland, Oregon#Intercity service|Intercity service]] section below for information about the many intercity bus and train services to and from Portland from outside the metro area.

