====Portland, OR Public Transportation Statistics====
The average amount of time people spend commuting with public transit in Portland, OR, for example to and from work, on a weekday is 90 min. 36% of public transit riders, ride for more than 2 hours every day. The average amount of time people wait at a stop or station for public transit is 14 min, while 21% of riders wait for over 20 minutes on average every day. The average distance people usually ride in a single trip with public transit is 8.2 km, while 18% travel for over 12 km in a single direction. <ref>{{cite web|title=Portland, OR Public Transportation Statistics|publisher= Global Public Transit Index by Moovit|url=https://moovitapp.com/insights/en/Moovit_Insights_Public_Transit_Index_USA_Portland_OR-144|accessdate=June 19, 2017}} [[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License].</ref>

==Cycling==
{{main|Cycling in Portland, Oregon}}

Bicycle use in Portland has been growing rapidly, having nearly tripled since 2001; for example, daily bicycle traffic on four of the Willamette River bridges has increased from 2,855 before 1992 to over 16,000 in {{as of|2008|alt=2008}}, partly due to improved facilities.<ref>[http://www.portlandonline.com/shared/cfm/image.cfm?id=217489 Portland Bicycle Counts 2008] ([[PDF]]), City of Portland</ref> Approximately 8% of commuters [[Bicycle commuting|bike to work]] in Portland, the highest proportion of any major U.S. city and about 10 times the national average.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dougherty|first=Conor|title='Youth Magnet' Cities Hit Midlife Crisis|date=May 16, 2009|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124242099361525009 |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=October 18, 2010}}</ref> By July 2016 through a 4-0 city council vote, Portland will have a [[Bicycle-sharing system|bike share]] program running with 600 bikes. The new bikes will be provided by Social Bicycles, and will be operated by [[Motivate (company)|Motivate]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.oregonlive.com/commuting/index.ssf/2015/09/portland_city_council_bike-sha.html|title = Portland City Council signs off on new bike-share program|last = Njus|first = Elliot|date = September 23, 2015|work = [[OregonLive.com|OregonLive]]|access-date = September 24, 2015|via = }}</ref>

==Walking==
According to a city video, in 1994 Portland became the first city to develop a pedestrian master plan.<ref>[http://media.ci.portland.or.us/safewalks/safewalks.html Portland Walks - Be Safe] from the City of Portland website</ref>  Blocks in the downtown area are only {{convert|200|ft}} long.  Many streets in the outer southwest section of the city lack sidewalks; however, this is partially made up with various off-street trails.<ref>[http://www.swtrails.org/ SW Urban Trails], a website of the neighborhood coalition for [[Neighborhoods of Portland, Oregon|southwest Portland]]</ref> A 2011 study by [[Walk Score]] ranked Portland the 12th most walkable of the fifty largest cities in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walkscore.com/rankings/?page=1|title=2011 City and Neighborhood Rankings |publisher=Walk Score |year=2011 |accessdate=Jan 23, 2013}}</ref>

The [[Gibbs Street Pedestrian Bridge]], a new pedestrian and bicycle bridge over I-5 near the [[Portland Aerial Tram]], opened in 2012.<ref name=oreg-12jul12>{{cite news|last=Koffman|first=Rebecca|title=New pedestrian and bicycle bridge across Interstate 5 opens Saturday in Southwest Portland |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 12, 2012 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2012/07/new_pedestrian_and_bicycle_bri.html |accessdate=August 10, 2012}}</ref>

==Traffic flow==
{{unreferenced section|date=May 2012}}
Many streets in Portland are one-way; streets in downtown Portland (Southwest Portland bounded by I-405 and the Willamette River) are virtually all one-way, forming a grid of alternating street traffic: for north-south streets, odd-numbered avenues (1st, 3rd, etc.) are southbound, while even-numbered avenues (2nd, 4th, etc.) are northbound, and similarly east-west streets alternate.  This is partly due to the streets in downtown Portland being relatively narrow ({{convert|64|ft}}).{{Clarify| question=how does narrow streets relate to alternating direction of travel?|date=February 2012}} This grid extends a short way west across I-405 into [[Goose Hollow, Portland, Oregon|Goose Hollow]], terminating at SW 18th Avenue, and extends to some degree north across Burnside into the Pearl District, particularly with the north-south streets extending into Old Town.

Most streets on the east side are two-way, but there are a number of [[one-way pair]]s along major routes:  Martin Luther King Jr. Blvd. (MLK)/Grand Avenue (the equivalent of 4th and 5th avenues), and 11th/12th east-west pairs are connected with bridges, with NE Couch/Burnside forming a pair east of the Burnside Bridge from 3rd to 14th avenues, SE Morrison/SE Belmont forming a pair from the [[Morrison Bridge]] to SE 25th Ave, and SE Madison/SE Hawthorne forming a pair from the [[Hawthorne Bridge]] to SE 12th Avenue.

